===Etymology 1===
{{unk|zh|Unclear}}. Various theories have been proposed:

* {{zh-ref|Starostin}} sets up {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*lăj||snake}}, comparing this with {{cog|lus|hlai-ba||a species of snake}} and {{cog|kac|palai||a species of iguana}}. He also compares it to {{cog|qfa-kms-pro|*dzuːi²||snake}}. {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} considers these {{cog|tbq}} forms to be unrelated.
* {{zh-ref|Matisoff (2003)}} relates it to {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-b/m-ruːl||snake}}, but this comparison is no longer held in STEDT.
* {{zh-ref|Sagart (2005)}} relates it to {{cog|tbq-lol-pro|*lay¹/²||python}}, which STEDT derives from {{cog|sit-pro|*g-lja(ŋ/k)||python}}, as well as {{cog|map-pro|*bulay||snake}}. Comparison with the {{cog|map}} form has been challenged by {{zh-ref|Orlandi (2018)}}.
* {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} notes similarity to {{cog|qfa-lic-pro|*ljaːɦ||snake}} (from Pre-Hlai ''*Cilaːɦ'') as well as to {{cog|map}} words, such as {{cog|rad|ala||snake}}, but considers the {{cog|qfa-tak}} forms to be possible borrowings from Chinese. (He does not seem to address the {{cog|map}} forms directly.) In his view, a more likely relationship is with the {{IPAchar|/-lé/}} in {{cog|km|រលេ||[[sinuously]], in a [[twisting]] or [[wiggling]] manner (as a snake swimming)}}. In Old Chinese, this also provides the second syllable in {{och-l|委蛇|[[winding]]; [[compliant]]; [[graceful]]|id=1,3}}. {{m|zh|蛇||the winding thing}} is then a euphemism for common Sino-Tibetan {{och-l|虺|snake|id=3}} for taboo reasons.
* {{zh-ref|Zhengzhang (2011)}} relates it to {{cog|map-pro|*SulaR||snake}}.

